olent conflicts? How were the bodies of fighters trained, nourished, and prepared for combat? How did they respond to wounds, torture and the ubiquitous risk of death?The articles present examples of body techniques of fighters and their perception throughout the Middle Ages. The geographical scope ranges from the Anglo-Scottish borderlands over Central Europe up to the Mediterranean World. This larger framework enables the reader to trace the similarities and differences of the cultural practice of "Killing and Being Killed" in various contexts.Contributions by Iain MacInnes, Alastair J. Macdonald, Bogdan-Petru Maleon, and others.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aCombatxHistoryyTo 1500vCongresses. 0aHuman bodyxPolitical aspectszEuropexHistoryyTo 1500vCongresses. 0aHuman bodyxPolitical aspectszScotlandxHistoryyTo 1500vCongresses. 0aMiddle AgesvCongresses. 0aMilitary history, MedievalvCongresses. 0aPolitical violencezEuropexHistoryyTo 1500vCongresses. 0aPolitical violencezScotlandxHistoryyTo 1500vCongresses. 4aConflict. 4aCultural History. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aEuropean History. 4aFight. 4aHistory. 4aMedieval History. 4aMiddle Ages. 4aViolence. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aConflict.  aCultural History.  aEarly Modern History.  aEuropean History.  aFight.  aHistory.  aMedieval History.  aMiddle Ages.  aViolence.1 aBerndt, Guido M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurkart, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJaquet, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1